post_text:
While the class of 2020 didn't get to end their senior year quite as planned, they definitely left an impact. Utilizing the money they would have spent on their senior trip, nine picnic tables were purchased and placed in the courtyard for future classes to enjoy. Teachers have been using them during class, and kids have been enjoying eating lunch in the fresh air.

Thank you class of 2020!

post_text: This year Geometric Battleship went virtual! It was the cadets vs Lt. Stottlemyer, and the Block 5 cadets successfully sunk three of Lt. Stottlemyer’s ships. Cadets launched their virtual cannons by reading off coordinates and in between their attempts they had to calculate the distance and midpoints of their two most recent coordinates. It was a fun way to end the week, learn more about the GeoGebra software, and to practice for next week’s test!

Anderson Preparatory Academy has been named a Purple Star Recipient!

The Purple Star designation honors schools displaying a significant commitment to service members, veterans, students, and families connected to our nation’s military.

In its first year, schools had to meet specific requirements to receive the Purple Star school designation. These include, assigning a point of contact for military families, passing a resolution supporting military students and families, guaranteeing interviews for service members and their immediate family who meet the minimum job qualifications, and more.

#JetPrideCadetPride

Middle School Volleyball tryouts will begin on Monday, August 10th after school from 3:30 until 5PM.

Athletes must have a physical on file in the athletic office. If you had a physical last year it is still good for this school year. If not, you need to get one.

Also, athletes and parents must register on FinalForms to participate. There is still a $50 fee for each sport besides football. Girls should have proper practice attire and with shoes and knee pads. They may be picked up at door S5 at 5 pm.

Contact Coach Burkett at jburkett@goapa.org or our Athletic Director, David Bradford, dbradford@goapa.org.

post_text:
7/30/2020

Dear APA Families,

We have FANTASTIC news to share! APA has been approved for the Community Eligibility Provision through the National School Lunch and School Breakfast programs for the 2020-2021 school year. CEP status means that APA can now provide FREE breakfast and lunch for ALL of our cadets at no charge to families. Your cadet will be automatically enrolled in the program and no documentation will be needed.

We are very grateful for the opportunity to be able to provide this service for your cadets!
Sincerely,

Commandant Barker

post_text:
Due to a supply chain disruption, the Anderson Preparatory Academy Board of Directors has voted to delay the start of school for students until Monday, August 10, 2020. Our start date for students was originally scheduled for Thursday, August 6, 2020. At this time, students will return in-person unless enrolled in the Virtual Academy.

Teachers will report August 3, 2020 as originally scheduled, and we will use the two additional days to provide additional professional development in order to better prepare our teachers for the upcoming school year.

Thank you for your continued patience and support as we navigate these unprecedented times.
text:

Our start date for students was originally scheduled for Thursday, August 6, 2020. At this time, students will return in-person unless enrolled in the Virtual Academy.

Teachers will report August 3, 2020 as originally scheduled, and we will use the two additional days to provide additional professional development in order to better prepare our teachers for the upcoming school year.

Thank you for your continued patience and support as we navigate these unprecedented times.

At today’s news conference, Governor Holcomb announced a new state mandate in regards to masks in schools. In compliance with this mandate, beginning Monday, July 27, 2020 and until further notice, masks are required at all times for all faculty, staff, visitors, and vendors as well as all students in grades 3-12. K-2 students will be highly encouraged to wear masks and must have a mask with them at all times in case of emergency.

APA is officially offering both in-person and virtual options this school year beginning on Thursday, August 6. Official plans will be released this Friday.

To enroll in our Virtual Academy, inquiries can be emailed to Angie Shively at ashively@goapa.org by Friday, July 24.

We are K-12 and tuition free! To enroll visit our website at https://www.goapa.org/Enroll.aspx.

Become a part of our APA Family. New students are welcome.

post_text:
Introducing our 2020 Valedictorian, Hanna Honarmandian, and Salutatorian, Raegan Fraley.

Hanna Honarmandian is Anderson Preparatory Academy’s 2020 Valedictorian. She is graduating first in her class. Hanna will be attending Purdue University studying in the Pre-Vet program with plans on earning her doctorate in veterinary medicine.

Raegan Fraley is Anderson Preparatory Academy’s 2020 Salutatorian. She is graduating second in her class with a 4.429 GPA. Raegan will be attending IUPUI in the Fall studying Elementary Education. She also has been awarded the renewable $7500 Next Generation Hoosier Teacher Scholarship.

We are so very proud of them.
Congratulations ladies!

From the Desk of Captain Graves:

I have been asked by several families how they can help their teens cope with stress during the pandemic. Teens are social by nature and isolation can be extra hard for them. I have shared this article with a few parents, but thought it would be relevant for everyone to read.

This article actually has questions you can ask your child to find out how they are doing and provide you with insight on how they may need help.
If you find you need help supporting your child please feel free to reach out to us at APA for help. We are here for you and your family.

﻿ www.psychologytoday.com/us/blog/nurturing-resilience/202003/what-teens-need-during-pandemic%3Famp

text: Director Miller’s update for the Academy:

post_text:
Pre-Academy Update:

I hope everyone is doing well and adjusting as well as possible to our new temporary normal.
This week the Pre Academy implemented the “week at a glance” E-Learning schedule for our families. Our hope is to help everyone feel a little more organized and less anxious during the next 7 weeks of E- Learning. I will be sending these out every Monday to all of our students and families via email. If you don’t receive one please contact me and I will make sure you get one and put you on our email list.
Our teachers are here to help you in any way we can and are reaching out to make personal contact with everyone. If you or your child have any questions concerning E-Learning, you need added to our email list, or you haven’t been in touch with anyone from APA please email me at kgraves@goapa.org.
We love each of you and want to be there for you in any way we can.

Remember WE ARE THE JETS! “When everything seems to be going against you, remember that a JET takes off against the wind not with it”- Henry Ford

Captain Graves

post_text:
APA ELEMENTARY - MARCH 19

By now, you are all probably aware that our Governor has mandated that all schools will be closed until at least May 1.

Our APA administration team is meeting on Monday to develop what eLearning will look like going forward. There are no assignments due this week nor next. No new eLearning assignments will begin until the week of March 30th.

Additionally, all state assessments, like IREAD (3rd grade only) and ILEARN (for 3rd/4th graders) are canceled for this school year.

Finally, as a reminder, we are here for you. As far as we can tell, we will be able to continue providing food services as our closure continues. I will continue to provide updates as soon as I have them, and I promise you that we will be as accommodating and adaptive as possible during these challenging times.

Stay safe,
Cpt. Fraley

ATTENTION ALL APA ELEMENTARY STUDENTS:

All elementary school e-learning assignments from 3/10-3/13 and 3/30-4/3 will be due no later than the Friday following our return to class (4/10). 4/10 is the end of the 5th grading period. Grades in Skyward will be updated by Tuesday, April 15th and report cards will go home on Friday, April 17th.

E-learning assignments for 3/30-4/3 will be posted to teacher blogs and remind 101s on Sunday, March 29th. Contact your child’s teacher directly with any questions. Mrs. Owens’ parents will find information for their students’ assignments on Captain Hornocker’s blog (including a new remind 101).

If anything changes, we will make updates to our expectations as soon as we are able. Our teachers and staff miss all of our kiddos! Please give them lots of hugs and love from us!

We will be CLOSED for elearning on Tuesday, 3/10/20, and Wednesday, 3/11/20. This will give our crew time to thoroughly disinfect the buildings. All after school activities for today, Tuesday, and Wednesday are cancelled.

We will re-evaluate our progress on Wednesday afternoon and a determination will be made if we will resume school on Thursday.

Amanda Cox is a 4th grade student in Lt. Wiles' class. She is one of APA's outstanding students! She utilized her leadership skills and a love for animals to develop a community service opportunity that would benefit the Animal Protection League of Anderson. She collected several items from the students at the elementary school and delivered it to the APL this week. Way to go Amanda! Keep up the great work!

#EmpoweringLeaders
shared_text:
The Animal Protection League Inc., Indiana
March 4 at 8:11 PM ·

Amanda Cox is a 4th grade student in Lt. Wiles' class at Anderson Preparatory Academy. She has a huge heart for all animals! She and her family volunteer at The Animal Protection League periodically and she understands the need we have at our facility. Because of this, she planned a school wide fundraiser for her elementary school that would help collect items for the APL. She did all the planning, including designing her own flyer. She then followed through with her plan by getting several students to help donate different items that the APL needed. Monday, they were finally able to bring in all of the stuff for the staff and animals!

Thank you so much, Amanda! We are overwhelmed by your kindness and generosity. You rock! 🐾

post_text:
It's National School Choice Week!

School choice is the process of allowing every family to choose the K-12 educational options that best fit their children. These options include all forms of education, from traditional public schools, to public charter schools, public magnet schools, private schools, online academies, and homeschooling.

Every child deserves an effective, challenging, and motivating education. Because each student has their own unique set of talents, interests, and challenges, a variety of options in education is crucial. School choice ensures that each student can find a learning environment that allows them to be inspired, successful, and happy.

Thank you for choosing us!

https://youtu.be/fsKozJdeLhI

post_text:
Last week in Lt. Stottlemyer’s geometry classes, cadets connected math with art by working together to build a Tier 5 Sierpinski Pyramid, which stands five feet tall and six feet wide. A Sierpinksi Pyramid is a fractal that’s based around an equilateral triangle being broken down into smaller equilateral triangles. It took three days to build the 1,024 individual pyramids and every cadet played a critical role in this creation.

Cadets are now motivated to build a Tier 6 pyramid, which would stand over 10 feet tall and require an additional 2,976 individual pyramids.

At noon today, 37 of our cadets boarded a bus to travel to San Antonio, Texas! On this trip cadets will see Lackland Air Force Base, attend a military ball, visit Silver Spurs Ranch, visit the Alamo Riverwalk, and spend a night aboard the USS Lexington!

JROTC learning come to life!

Dear Parents or Guardians:

The Flu has hit the school and we need your help to keep it from spreading. Symptoms could be but are not limited to; headache, vomiting, fever/ chills, diarrhea, cough, sore throat, body or muscle aches, or tiredness out of the norm.

If your cadet is sick please keep them home. Attached are some informational pages on it as well.

Much appreciation,
School Nurses

post_text:
Sophomores participated in Mrs. Rue’s fifth annual Hunger Games Day! A day in which the book comes to life! 10th graders participated in archery, herbology with APA alum, Sam Hockwalt, “What Are the Odds?” math station with Mr. Stottlemyer, and self defense with Elwood Police Officer, Tyler Irwin!

Thank you to those who came in and helped teach our students outside of the classroom!

post_text:
1st and 2nd grade cadets participated in an enrichment class on December 7th presented by the Indiana Academy for Science, Mathematics and Humanities called Build it, Break it! Students participating in this free class learned about science and engineering while creating boats and structures with popsicle sticks and other materials.

On December 14th, 3rd and 4th grade cadets will get their turn at this exciting class! Pre-registration is required and the class is limited to 20 students. Registration forms went home on Friday, Dec. 6 with cadets (and were posted here on FB) and are due back no later than Wednesday, December 11th.

post_text: The Lady Jets Basketball team players took initiative and organized a fundraiser when they heard of a fellow Shenandoah basketball player who had lost her belongings and dog in a house fire. The players planned, organized and conducted a half time free throw shooting contest at 2 events and raised over $300. Today, they visited her at school to present their gift.
